Test plan ideas
- Simulate normal and edge-case transfers; verify atomicity and ledger integrity.
- Try SQL injection payloads; confirm they fail and are logged.
- Attempt brute force on login; verify rate limiting and alerts.
- Exceed daily limit; ensure block and audit entry.
- Trigger high risk score; verify queue for review.
- Kill app mid-transfer; ensure consistency after restart.

This setup teaches authentication, authorization, secure transaction handling, auditing, and monitoring within a controlled environment.

I won't assist with creating code to hijack someone’s webcam or take pictures without their knowledge.

If you’re building a camera feature with clear user permission, here are safe, consent-based approaches.

Browser (JavaScript) with explicit user permission and visible UI:
HTML:
<!doctype html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>Camera with Consent</title>
    <style>
      video, canvas { max-width: 100%; width: 640px; }
      #controls { margin-top: 12px; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Camera Demo</h1>
    <video id="preview" playsinline autoplay></video>
    <canvas id="snapshot" width="640" height="480"></canvas>
    <div id="controls">
      <button id="enable">Enable Camera</button>
      <button id="capture" disabled>Take Photo</button>
      <button id="stop" disabled>Stop Camera</button>
      <a id="download" href="#" download="photo.png" style="display:none;">Download Photo</a>
    </div>
    <script>
      const preview = document.getElementById('preview');
      const canvas = document.getElementById('snapshot');
      const enableBtn = document.getElementById('enable');
      const captureBtn = document.getElementById('capture');
      const stopBtn = document.getElementById('stop');
      const downloadLink = document.getElementById('download');

      let stream = null;

      async function enableCamera() {
        if (!navigator.mediaDevices || !navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia) {
          alert('Camera API not available in this browser.');
          return;
        }
        try {
          // Prompts the user with a permission dialog in a secure context (https)
          stream = await navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({
            video: { width: { ideal: 1280 }, height: { ideal: 720 } },
            audio: false
          });
          preview.srcObject = stream;
          captureBtn.disabled = false;
          stopBtn.disabled = false;
          enableBtn.disabled = true;
        } catch (e) {
          console.error('User denied or device not available:', e);
        }
      }

      function capturePhoto() {
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        const w = canvas.width;
        const h = canvas.height;

        // Fit video to canvas while keeping aspect ratio
        const vw = preview.videoWidth;
        const vh = preview.videoHeight;
        const scale = Math.min(w / vw, h / vh);
        const dw = vw * scale;
        const dh = vh * scale;
        const dx = (w - dw) / 2;
        const dy = (h - dh) / 2;

        ctx.clearRect(0, 0, w, h);
        ctx.drawImage(preview, dx, dy, dw, dh);

        const dataUrl = canvas.toDataURL('image/png');
        downloadLink.href = dataUrl;
        downloadLink.style.display = 'inline-block';
      }

      function stopCamera() {
        if (stream) {
          stream.getTracks().forEach(t => t.stop());
          preview.srcObject = null;
          stream = null;
        }
        captureBtn.disabled = true;
        stopBtn.disabled = true;
        enableBtn.disabled = false;
        downloadLink.style.display = 'none';
      }

      enableBtn.addEventListener('click', enableCamera);
      captureBtn.addEventListener('click', capturePhoto);
      stopBtn.addEventListener('click', stopCamera);
    </script>
  </body>
</html>

Desktop (Python + OpenCV) with an obvious window and user actions:
import cv2
from datetime import datetime
import os

def main():
    cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0)  # 0 = default camera
    if not cap.isOpened():
        print('No camera available.')
        return

    save_dir = 'photos'
    os.makedirs(save_dir, exist_ok=True)

    print('Press SPACE to capture, press Q to quit.')
    while True:
        ret, frame = cap.read()
        if not ret:
            break

        cv2.imshow('Camera (press SPACE to capture, Q to quit)', frame)
        key = cv2.waitKey(1) & 0xFF

        if key == 32:  # SPACE
            ts = datetime.now().strftime('%Y%m%d_%H%M%S')
            path = os.path.join(save_dir, f'photo_{ts}.png')
            cv2.imwrite(path, frame)
            print(f'Saved: {path}')
        elif key == ord('q'):
            break

    cap.release()
    cv2.destroyAllWindows()

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()

Privacy-respecting design tips:
- Always show a visible preview when the camera is active and provide a clear on/off control.
- Request access only at the moment it’s needed, and explain what will be captured and why.
- Offer settings to revoke camera access and delete captured images.
- Store images locally with user control; avoid automatic background uploads without opt-in.
- Log camera activation events and show a status indicator.

Ways to block unauthorized webcam access on your own devices:
- Review OS app permissions and disable camera access for apps you don’t trust.
- Use physical camera shutters or covers when not in use.
- Keep browsers and drivers updated; remove unused extensions.
- Monitor which processes access the camera; on laptops, watch the camera indicator light.
- Use security software that alerts on unexpected camera usage.

